    {
      "id": "1a76adc5_6bf77cf6",
      "file_path": "ONAP-PDP-REST/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pdp/rest/config/PDPApiAuth.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 119,
      "message": "I am not sure if thats a correct message Jorge.  This is not checking if the username is provided, it checks if @ is in the username so that if it is not it will append @ + aafPolicyNameSpace to the userNamePass.  If there were no username it would not even make it to this code and would log error and return false on line 132 and 133.  I can make it a warn and return false here but I would prefer to keep the log message the same or maybe we should say \"invalid username\".",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 805,
        "name": "Michael Mokry",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "michael.mokry@att.com",
        "username": "mmokry"
      },
      "updated": "2018-09-25 15:57:47.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "1a76adc5_d06afd80",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "1a76adc5_ab6274ab",
      "file_path": "ONAP-PDP-REST/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pdp/rest/config/PDPApiAuth.java",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 119,
      "message": "Actually I cannot return false here... if the username comes containing @ it seems to be assuming the dns is appended to it and will need to be able to continue through the process.  If I return false here using a username like demo@people.osaaf.org would then return false even though its a valid username.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 805,
        "name": "Michael Mokry",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "michael.mokry@att.com",
        "username": "mmokry"
      },
      "updated": "2018-09-25 16:01:42.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "1a76adc5_d06afd80",
      "unresolved": false
    },
